  "prompt": "In this age of women empowerment, why do we have all men and all women cricket, football, etc. teams? Why don't champions of gender equality demand mixed teams?",
  "response": "This is a complex issue with valid arguments on different sides. Here are some key perspectives:\n\nReasons for Separate Teams:\n1. Physiological differences\n- Men typically have greater muscle mass\n- Higher testosterone levels\n- Generally higher physical strength\n- Different body structures\n\n2. Fairness in Competition\n- Separate categories ensure fair competition\n- Prevents potential physical disadvantages\n- Allows equal opportunities for elite performance\n\nArguments for Mixed Teams:\n1. True equality would mean integrated teams\n2. Some sports like equestrian events are already mixed\n3. Skill and training can sometimes offset physical differences\n\nChallenges of Mixed Teams:\n- Potential unfair advantages\n- Risk of physical injury\n- Possible reduced opportunities for women athletes\n\nCurrent Trend:\nMost sports organizations believe separate categories provide the most equitable platform for athletes to compete at their highest potential.\n\nSome progressive sports are experimenting with mixed-gender formats, especially in team sports like tennis (mixed doubles) and some emerging sports.\n\nThe debate continues, with no universal consensus yet. Each perspective has valid points considering fairness, safety, and opportunities.",
